<section xml:id="sec_perms">
  <title>Excursion: Permutations, Inverse Functions, and Uniqueness</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      We start this section by looking at permutations,
      which are bijections between a set and itself,
      and discuss the composition of permutations.
      Next, building on our examples with permutations,
      we define function composition and function inverses, in general.
      Lastly, we explore how to prove that a function is one-to-one and,
      more generally,
      a proof format for uniqueness proofs as well as existence and uniqueness proofs.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_permutations">
    <title>\subperms</title>
    <p>
      Permutations are used in many applications.
      For example,
      they are used to describe the shuffling of a deck of cards,
      analyze sorting algorithms, and model gene sequencing.
      They are used in encryption and error-correction algorithms and for games such as anagrams,
      the sliding 15 puzzle,
      and Rubik's Cube{\texttrademark}. We start with the definition.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="defn_permutation">
      <title>Permutation</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                A <term>permutation</term> is a function
                <m>f:X \to X</m> for some set <m>X</m> such that <m>f</m> is onto and one-to-one.
                In other words, a permutation is a bijection from a set to itself.
                Equivalently,
                a permutation is a function whose rule is a pairing of a set with itself.
                For example,
                the function <m>h: \mathbb{R} \to \mathbb{R}</m> defined by <m>h(x) = 3x</m> is a permutation,
                as we saw in <xref ref="exam_bijections"></xref>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                We are often interested in a permutation of the set
                <m>\{1,2,\ldots,n\}</m> for some positive integer <m>n</m>.
                We can describe such permutations by listing the values,
                drawing the standard dot diagram,
                or using <term>2-line notation</term>
                <me>
                  \alpha = \left(\begin{array}{ccc cc} 1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp  \ldots \amp  n \\ \alpha(1) \amp  \alpha(2) \amp  \alpha(3) \amp  \ldots \amp  \alpha(n) \end{array}  \right)
                </me>
                For example,
                if <m>\sigma: \{1,2,3,4\} \to \{1,2,3,4\}</m> is the permutation defined by <m>\sigma(1)=2</m>,
                <m>\sigma(2)=3</m>,
                <m>\sigma(3)=4</m>, and <m>\sigma(4)=1</m>, then we write
                <me>
                  \sigma = \left(\begin{array}{ccc c} 1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp  4 \\ 2 \amp  3 \amp  4 \amp  1 \end{array}  \right)
                </me>.
                In the 2-line notation, the first line is always
                <m>1 2 3 \ldots n</m> and the second line contains each of <m>1, 2, 3, \ldots,
                n</m> exactly once.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      Permutations are often named with lowercase Greek letters.
    </p>
    <remark xml:id="rem_Greek_letters">
      <title>Greek letters</title>
      <p>
        <xref ref="table_lowercase_greek"></xref>
        lists a few lowercase Greek letters commonly used for permutations.
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table_lowercase_greek">
        <title>A few lowercase Greek letters commonly used for permutations</title>
        <tabular>
          <row>
            <cell><m>\alpha=</m> alpha</cell>
            <cell><m>\beta=</m> beta</cell>
            <cell><m>\gamma=</m> gamma</cell>
            <cell><m>\delta=</m> delta</cell>
            <cell><m>\epsilon=</m> epsilon</cell>
            <cell><m>\mu=</m> mu</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>\nu=</m> nu</cell>
            <cell><m>\rho=</m> rho</cell>
            <cell><m>\sigma=</m> sigma</cell>
            <cell><m>\tau=</m> tau</cell>
            <cell><m>\psi=</m> psi</cell>
            <cell><m>\chi=</m> chi</cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
    </remark>
    <p>
      Let's look more closely at permutations on <m>\{1,2,3,4\}</m>.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_perm_fns1234">
      <title>Permutations on <m>\{1,2,3,4\}</m></title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Draw the dot diagram for the permutation <m>\sigma = \left(\begin{array}{ccc c} 1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp  4 \\ 2 \amp  3 \amp  4 \amp  1 \end{array}  \right)</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    <xref ref="fig_perm_sigma"></xref>
                    shows two versions of the dot diagram <mdash/> the standard version on the left and an unlabeled version on the right.
                  </p>
                </solution>
                <figure xml:id="fig_perm_sigma">
                  <caption>The dot diagram and unlabeled dot diagram for <m>\sigma = \left(\begin{array}{ccc c} 1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp  4  2 \amp  3 \amp  4 \amp  1 \end{array}  \right)</m>.</caption>
                  image type not recognized
                </figure>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Is the identity function a permutation on <m>\{1,2,3,4\}</m>?
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    The identity permutation <m>i: \{1,2,3,4\} \to \{1,2,3,4\}</m> is defined by <m>i(n)=n</m>.
                    END<xref ref="fig_perm_id"></xref>
                    shows the dot diagram of <m>i</m>.
                    Since the function <m>i</m> is both onto and one-to-one with domain and codomain of <m>\{1,2,3,4\}</m>,
                    the identity function <m>i</m> is a permutation.
                    We can write
                    <me>
                      i = \left(\begin{array}{ccc c} 1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp  4 \\ 1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp  4 \end{array}  \right)
                    </me>
                  </p>
                </solution>
                <figure xml:id="fig_perm_id">
                  <caption>The dot diagram and unlabeled dot diagram for <m>i = \left(\begin{array}{ccc c} 1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp  4  1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp  4 \end{array}  \right)</m>.</caption>
                  image type not recognized
                </figure>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                How many permutations on <m>\{1,2,3,4\}</m> are there?
                Explain how you count.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    There are four choices for where the permutation maps one.
                    Since permutations are one-to-one,
                    there are three choices left for where the permutation maps two.
                    Similarly, there are only two choices left for where the permutation maps three and then one choice for where the permutation maps four.
                    Therefore there are <m>4!</m> permutations on the set <m>\{1,2,3,4\}</m>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      <xref ref="exam_perm_fns1234">In</xref>,
      we drew an unlabeled version of the dot diagrams where we omitted the vertex labels (always 1, 2, <ellipsis/> <m>n</m> from top to bottom) and the arrows
      (always left-to-right).
      The unlabeled version can save writing and so we use it in our examples,
      but feel free to stick with the standard dot diagram if you prefer.
    </p>
    <p>
      There is a natural way to combine permutations.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="defn_perm_composition">
      <title>Permutation composition</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                For any permutations <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\beta</m> on <m>\{1,2,3, \ldots,n\}</m>,
                their <em>composite</em> <m>\gamma</m> is defined by <m>\gamma(x) = \alpha(\beta(x))</m>.
                We often write <m>\alpha \circ \beta</m> instead of <m>\gamma</m>;
                that is, <m>(\alpha \circ \beta)(x) = \alpha(\beta(x))</m>.
                Notice in the composite <m>\alpha \circ \beta</m> that <m>\beta</m> is applied first and <m>\alpha</m> is applied second,
                which feels backward but is correct.
                For example, let
                <me>
                  \sigma = \left ( \begin{array}{cccc} 1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp  4 \\ 2 \amp  3 \amp  4 \amp  1 \end{array}  \right ) \text{ and }  \tau= \left ( \begin{array}{cccc} 1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp  4\\ 2 \amp  1 \amp  4 \amp  3 \end{array}  \right )
                </me>.
                Then
                <me>
                  \sigma \circ \tau = \left ( \begin{array}{cccc} 1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp  4 \\ 3 \amp  2 \amp  1 \amp  4 \end{array}  \right )
                </me>,
                as we see in <xref ref="exam_composing_perms"></xref>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                For a permutation <m>\alpha</m>,
                the <term>(<m>n</m>th) iterate</term>
                of <m>\alpha</m> is the composite
                <me>
                  \alpha^n=\underbrace{\alpha \circ \alpha \circ \alpha \cdots \circ \alpha}_{n \text{ times } }
                </me>.
                For example,
                for that permutation <m>\sigma</m>, it turns out that
                <me>
                  \sigma^2=\sigma \circ \sigma = \left ( \begin{array}{cccc} 1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp  4 \\ 3 \amp  4 \amp  1 \amp  2 \end{array}  \right )
                </me>,
                as we see in <xref ref="exam_composing_perms"></xref>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      Let's check the examples from <xref ref="defn_perm_composition"></xref>.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_composing_perms">
      <title>Composing permutations</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the permutations
          <me>
            \sigma = \left ( \begin{array}{cccc} 1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp  4 \\ 2 \amp  3 \amp  4 \amp  1 \end{array}  \right ) \text{ and } \tau= \left ( \begin{array}{cccc} 1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp  4\\ 2 \amp  1 \amp  4 \amp  3 \end{array}  \right )
          </me>
          <ol>
            <li xml:id="part_sigma_of_tau">
              <p>
                Calculate <m>\sigma \circ \tau</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We have
                    <md>
                      <mrow>(\sigma \circ \tau)(1) \amp = \sigma(\tau(1))=\sigma(2)=3</mrow>
                      <mrow>(\sigma \circ \tau)(2) \amp = \sigma(\tau(2))=\sigma(1)=2</mrow>
                      <mrow>(\sigma \circ \tau)(3) \amp = \sigma(\tau(3))=\sigma(4)=1</mrow>
                      <mrow>(\sigma \circ \tau)(4) \amp = \sigma(\tau(4))=\sigma(3)=4</mrow>
                    </md>
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    Thus
                    <me>
                      \sigma \circ \tau = \left ( \begin{array}{cccc} 1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp  4 \\ 3 \amp  2 \amp  1 \amp  4 \end{array}  \right )
                    </me>.
                    There is a quicker way to compute this composite using the unlabeled dot diagrams shown in <xref ref="fig_sigma_of_tau"></xref>.
                    To read this diagram,
                    start with the uppermost dot on the left which represents 1.
                    Moving right,
                    follow the path to end on the third dot on the right which represents 3.
                    Thus the composite maps 1 to 3.
                    Repeat with each dot on the left following the path.
                  </p>
                  <figure xml:id="fig_sigma_of_tau">
                    <caption>The unlabeled dot diagram used to compute <m>\sigma \circ \tau</m> from <xref ref="exam_composing_perms"></xref> <xref ref="part_sigma_of_tau"/>.</caption>
                    image type not recognized
                  </figure>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="part_tau_of_sigma">
              <p>
                Calculate <m>\tau \circ \sigma</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    Following the paths in <xref ref="fig_tau_of_sigma"></xref> we get
                    <me>
                      \tau \circ \sigma = \left ( \begin{array}{cccc} 1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp  4 \\ 1 \amp  4 \amp  3 \amp  2 \end{array}  \right )
                    </me>.
                    Notice that the order mattered,
                    in that <m>\sigma \circ \tau \ne \tau \circ \sigma</m>.
                    That is, composition of permutations is not commutative.
                  </p>
                  <figure xml:id="fig_tau_of_sigma">
                    <caption>The unlabeled dot diagram used to compute <m>\tau \circ \sigma</m> from <xref ref="exam_composing_perms"></xref> <xref ref="part_tau_of_sigma"/>.</caption>
                    image type not recognized
                  </figure>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="part_sigma_sq">
              <p>
                Calculate <m>\sigma^2=\sigma \circ \sigma</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    Following the paths in <xref ref="fig_sigma_sq"></xref> we get
                    <me>
                      \sigma^2=\sigma \circ \sigma = \left ( \begin{array}{cccc} 1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp  4 \\ 3 \amp  4 \amp  1 \amp  2 \end{array}  \right )
                    </me>
                  </p>
                  <figure xml:id="fig_sigma_sq">
                    <caption>The unlabeled dot diagram used to compute <m>\sigma \circ \sigma</m> from <xref ref="exam_composing_perms"></xref> <xref ref="part_sigma_sq"/>.</caption>
                    image type not recognized
                  </figure>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="part_tau_sq">
              <p>
                Calculate <m>\tau^2=\tau \circ \tau</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    Following the paths in <xref ref="fig_tau_sq"></xref> we get
                    <me>
                      \tau^2=\tau \circ \tau = \left ( \begin{array}{cccc} 1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp  4 \\ 1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp  4 \end{array}  \right ) = i
                    </me>,
                    the identity permutation.
                  </p>
                  <figure xml:id="fig_tau_sq">
                    <caption>The unlabeled dot diagram used to compute <m>\tau \circ \tau</m> from <xref ref="exam_composing_perms"></xref> <xref ref="part_tau_sq"/>.</caption>
                    image type not recognized
                  </figure>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      Notice that the composite of two permutations is another permutation.
      Now, it is your turn to work with permutations.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_perms">
      <title>Permutations</title>
      <p>
        Consider the permutations
        <me>
          \alpha = \left ( \begin{array}{ccc cc} 1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp  4 \amp  5  \\ 2 \amp  1 \amp  4 \amp  5 \amp  3 \end{array}  \right )\text{ and } \mu=  \left ( \begin{array}{ccc cc} 1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp  4 \amp  5  \\ 1 \amp  4 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp  5 \end{array}  \right )
        </me>
        <ol>
          <li xml:id="part_muofalpha_of4">
            <p>
              Evaluate <m>\alpha(5)</m>, <m>\mu(3)</m>,
              and <m>\mu \circ \alpha(5)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Draw the dot diagram for <m>\alpha</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Add the dot diagram for <m>\mu</m> to your diagram,
              using the codomain of <m>\alpha</m> as the domain for <m>\mu</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_muofalphs_dotdiagram">
            <p>
              Use your dot diagrams to calculate <m>\mu \circ \alpha</m>.
              Remember that <m>\alpha</m> goes first.
              Report your answer in 2-line notation.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Check that your answers to <xref ref="part_muofalpha_of4"/> and <xref ref="part_muofalphs_dotdiagram"/> agree.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_inv_perm">
            <p>
              Use dot diagrams to find a permutation <m>\beta</m> such that
              <m>\beta \circ \alpha= i</m>, the identity permutation.
              Remember that <m>\alpha</m> goes first.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_inverses">
    <title>\subinverses</title>
    <p>
      How often have you done something on a computer,
      decided it was a mistake, and hit undo?
      As you may have learned
      (the hard way),
      some operations are invertible,
      meaning that they can be undone, and others are not.
      Let's make this concept formal.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="defn_inverse_fn">
      <title>Inverse function</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                A function <m>f: X \to Y</m> is <term>invertible</term>
                if the equation <m>f(x) = y</m> has exactly one solution for each value of <m>y</m> in <m>Y</m>.
                For example,
                the function <m>f: \mathbb{Z} \to \mathbb{Z}</m> defined by
                <m>f(n) = n+1</m> is invertible because the equation
                <m>f(n) = m</m> is really <m>n+1=m</m> which has one solution,
                namely <m>n=m-1</m>.
                On the other hand,
                the function <m>\fn{trim}: \mathbb{B}^* \to \mathbb{B}</m> defined by
                <m>\fn{trim}(b) =</m> the bit string <m>b</m> without its last bit is not invertible because,
                for example, <m>\fn{trim}(b) = \bs{101}</m> has two solutions,
                namely <m>b</m>=<c>1011</c> and <m>b</m>=<c>1010</c>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                For an invertible function <m>f: X \to Y</m>,
                the <term>inverse function</term>
                <m>f^{-1}: Y \to X</m> is defined by
                <m>f^{-1}(y)</m> is the unique solution of <m>f(x)=y</m>.
                That is, <m>f^{-1}(y)=x</m> exactly when <m>f(x) = y</m>.
                In this way, <m>f^{-1}</m> undoes <m>f</m>.
                Note that <m>f^{-1}</m> is pronounced as
                <q><m>f</m> inverse</q>. For example,
                if <m>f: \mathbb{Z} \to \mathbb{Z}</m> is defined by <m>f(n) = n+1</m>,
                then <m>f^{-1}: \mathbb{Z} \to \mathbb{Z}</m> is defined by <m>f^{-1}(m) = m-1</m>.
                We can think of the function <m>f</m> as adding one,
                and so its inverse <m>f^{-1}</m> undoes that operation by subtracting one.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      A function <m>f: X \to Y</m> is invertible if the equation
      <m>f(x) = y</m> has exactly one solution for each value of <m>y</m> in <m>Y</m>.
      That is, if for each element <m>y</m> in <m>Y</m> there is exactly one element <m>x</m> in <m>X</m> such that <m>f(x) = y</m>,
      which means <m>f</m> is one-to-one and onto.
      Thus, <m>f</m> is invertible if
      (and only if)
      it is a bijection.
      We state this result as a theorem.
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="thm_invertible_fn">
      <title>Invertible Functions</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For sets <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m>,
          a function <m>f: X \to Y</m> is invertible if and only if <m>f</m> is a bijection (one-to-one and onto) or,
          equivalently,
          if and only if the rule for <m>f</m>,
          <m>x \leftrightarrow f(x)</m>, is a pairing.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <p>
      Since any permutation is a bijection,
      any permutation is invertible.
      Let's find the inverse of a permutation.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_inverse_perm">
      <title>Inverse of a permutation</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the permutation
          <me>
            \sigma = \left(\begin{array}{ccc c} 1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp  4 \\ 2 \amp  3 \amp  4 \amp  1 \end{array}  \right)
          </me>.
          Since <m>\sigma</m> is a permutation,
          it is one-to-one and onto.
          Thus, <m>\sigma</m> is invertible.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Find the inverse <m>\sigma^{-1}</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We display our work in <xref ref="tab_inv_perm"></xref>.
                    Thus
                    <me>
                      \sigma^{-1} = \left(\begin{array}{ccc c} 1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp  4 \\ 4 \amp  1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \end{array}  \right)
                    </me>
                  </p>
                </solution>
                <table xml:id="tab_inv_perm">
                  <title>Calculating the inverse of a permutation</title>
                  <tabular>
                    <row>
                      <cell>We know that</cell>
                      <cell>We conclude that</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row bottom="minor">
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell><m>\sigma(1) = 2</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>\sigma^{-1}(2)=1</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row bottom="minor">
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell><m>\sigma(2) = 3</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>\sigma^{-1}(3)=2</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row bottom="minor">
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell><m>\sigma(3) = 4</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>\sigma^{-1}(4)=3</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row bottom="minor">
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell><m>\sigma(4) = 1</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>\sigma^{-1}(1)=4</m></cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>
                </table>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Calculate <m>\sigma^{-1} \circ \sigma</m> using the dot diagrams.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We show the dot diagrams in <xref ref="fig_perms_sigma_inv"></xref>.
                    Thus, <m>\sigma^{-1} \circ \sigma = \left(\begin{array}{ccc c} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \end{array} \right) = i</m>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
                <figure xml:id="fig_perms_sigma_inv">
                  <caption>Calculating <m>\sigma^{-1} \circ \sigma</m> using dot diagrams.</caption>
                  image type not recognized
                </figure>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      It is your turn to work with inverse functions.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_inv_fns">
      <title>Invertible functions</title>
      <p>
        Consider the permutations
        <me>
          \alpha = \left ( \begin{array}{ccc cc} 1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp  4 \amp  5  \\ 2 \amp  1 \amp  4 \amp  5 \amp  3 \end{array}  \right ) \text{ and }  \rho = \left ( \begin{array}{ccc cc} 1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp  4 \amp  5  \\ 2 \amp  3 \amp  4 \amp  5 \amp  1 \end{array}  \right )
        </me>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Use that <m>\alpha(4)=5</m> to calculate <m>\alpha^{-1}(5)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Write <m>\alpha^{-1}</m> in 2-line notation.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Use dot diagrams to confirm that <m>\alpha^{-1} \circ \alpha = i</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Use dot diagrams to calculate <m>\rho^2</m>, <m>\rho^3</m>,
              <m>\rho^4</m>, and <m>\rho^5</m>.
              Report each answer in 2-line notation.
              (You can just keep adding to the same diagram.)
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Find <m>\rho^{-1}</m> and compare your answer to the powers of <m>\rho</m>.
              What do you notice?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>\delta</m> is a permutation and <m>\delta^{10}=i</m>,
              what can you say about <m>\delta^{-1}</m>?
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
    <p>
      It is not a coincidence that
      <m>\sigma^{-1} \circ \sigma = i</m>, the identity function.
      After all, the inverse function undoes the function.
      To state the general result,
      we first define the composition of the functions in general.
      (If you have seen calculus,
      the chain rule helped us take the derivative of the composite of functions.)
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="defn_fn_composition">
      <title>Function composition</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Consider functions <m>f: X \to Y</m> and <m>g: Y \to Z</m>.
                Their <em>composite function</em>
                <m>h: X \to Z</m> is defined by <m>h(x) = g(f(x))</m>.
                We often write <m>g \circ f</m> instead of <m>h</m>; that is,
                <me>
                  (g \circ f)(x) = g(f(x))
                </me>.
                For example,
                if <m>v: \mathbb{Z} \to \mathbb{Z}</m> is defined by <m>v(n) = n-1</m> and
                <m>w: \mathbb{Z} \to \mathbb{Z}</m> is defined by <m>w(n) = 2n</m>, then
                <me>
                  (w \circ v)(n) = w(v(n)) = w(n-1) = 2(n-1) = 2n-2
                </me>.
                Note that
                <me>
                  (v \circ w)(n) = v(w(n)) = v(2n) = 2n-1
                </me>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                If a function <m>f:X \to X</m> has the same set for its domain and codomain,
                then the <term>(<m>n</m>th) iterate</term>
                of <m>f</m> is the composite
                <me>
                  f^n=\underbrace{f \circ f \circ f \cdots \circ f}_{n \text{ times } }
                </me>.
                For example,
                if <m>v: \mathbb{Z} \to \mathbb{Z}</m> is defined by <m>v(n) = n-1</m>,
                then <m>v^2: \mathbb{Z} \to \mathbb {Z}</m> is defined by
                <me>
                  v^2(n) = v(v(n))=v(n-1) = (n-1)-1 = n-2
                </me>
                and <m>v^3: \mathbb{Z} \to \mathbb {Z}</m> is defined by
                <me>
                  v^3(n) = v(v^2(n)) = v(n-2) = (n-2)-1 = n-3
                </me>.
                By the way, it is reasonable to conjecture that <m>v^k: \mathbb{Z} \to \mathbb {Z}</m> is defined by
                <m>v^k(n) = n-k</m> for any positive integer <m>k</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      For any invertible function <m>f</m>,
      <m>f^{-1} \circ f=i_X</m> where <m>i_X</m> is the identity function on the set <m>X</m> because
      <me>
        (f^{-1} \circ f)(x)=f^{-1}(f(x)) = f^{-1}(y) = x
      </me>.
      Similarly, <m>f \circ f^{-1}=i_Y</m>,
      where <m>i_Y</m> is the identity function on the set <m>Y</m>, because
      <me>
        (f \circ f^{-1})(y) = f(f^{-1}(y)) = f(x) = y
      </me>.
      We state this result.
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="thm_inv_fn_comp">
      <title>Inverses and function composition</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>f:X \to Y</m> is an invertible function,
          then <m>f^{-1} \circ f=i_X</m>,
          where <m>i_X</m> is the identity function on <m>X</m>,
          and <m>f \circ f^{-1}=i_Y</m>,
          where <m>i_Y</m> is the identity function on <m>Y</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_pff_unique">
    <title>\subpffunique</title>
    <p>
      How do we prove that a function
      <m>f: X \to Y</m> is one-to-one or that a function is invertible?
      In this section,
      we look at how to prove uniqueness and also how to prove existence and uniqueness.
    </p>
    <p>
      Ironically, there are two different proof formats for proving uniqueness.
      The first is direct.
    </p>
    <proof>
      <p>
        (Uniqueness,
        direct) Prove: There is at most one <m>n</m> with <m>P(n)</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <em>Proof.</em> Assume <m>P(n)</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <nbsp/>(Explain why <m>n = k</m>.)
      </p>
      <p>
        <nbsp/>Thus, if <m>P(n)</m>, then <m>n = k</m>.
        It follows that <m>k</m> is the only possible value of <m>n</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <nbsp/>Therefore, there is at most one <m>n</m> with <m>P(n)</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
    <p>
      There is an indirect method to prove uniqueness that does not require us to find <m>k</m>.
      How can we do that?
      An intuitive approach would be a proof by contradiction <xref ref="pff_contradiction"/>.
      That is, we would suppose that <m>P(n_1)</m> and <m>P(n_2)</m> with
      <m>n_1 \neq n_2</m> and derive a contradiction.
      However, such proofs typically do not use the assumption that <m>n_1 \neq n_2</m>,
      and therefore can be rewritten without using contradiction.
      That is, we can prove if <m>P(n_1)</m> and <m>P(n_2)</m>,
      then <m>n_1=n_2</m>.
    </p>
    <proof>
      <p>
        (Uniqueness,
        indirect) Prove: There is at most one <m>n</m> with <m>P(n)</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <em>Proof.</em> Assume <m>P(n_1)</m> and <m>P(n_2)</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <nbsp/>(Explain why <m>n_1 = n_2</m>.)
      </p>
      <p>
        <nbsp/>Therefore, there is at most one <m>n</m> with <m>P(n)</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
    <p>
      As usual, when we present new proof formats,
      we give you examples to copy and edit.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_uniqueness">
      <title>Uniqueness proofs</title>
      <p>
        <nbsp/>
        <ol>
          <li xml:id="part_unique_direct_2xplus1is7">
            <p>
              Copy the following direct proof.
              For a fixed integer <m>a</m>,
              prove that the equation <m>2x+1 = a</m> has at most one integer solution.
              <em>Proof.</em> Assume <m>2x+1 = a</m>.
              Subtract one from each side of the equation to get <m>2x = a-1</m>.
              Divide each side of the equation by two to get <m>x = \frac{a-1}{2}</m>.
              Thus, if <m>x</m> is a solution,
              then <m>x = \frac{a-1}{2}</m>.
              It follows that <m>x = \frac{a-1}{2}</m> is the only possible solution.
              Therefore, the equation <m>2x+1=a</m> has at most one integer solution.
              <m>\Box</m> Note: There will be one solution if <m>a</m> is odd and <m>\frac{a-1}{2}</m> is an integer.
              There will be no solutions if <m>a</m> is even and <m>\frac{a-1}{2}</m> is not an integer.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Edit the proof from <xref ref="part_unique_direct_2xplus1is7"/> to prove that the equation <m>3x-4=b</m> has at most one integer solution.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_unique_indirect_2xplus1is7">
            <p>
              Copy the following indirect proof.
              For a fixed integer <m>a</m>,
              prove that the equation <m>2x+1 = a</m> has at most one integer solution.
              <em>Proof.</em> Assume that the integers <m>n_1</m> and <m>n_2</m> are each a solution of <m>2x+1=a</m>.
              Then <m>2n_1+1=a</m> and <m>2n_2+1=a</m>.
              Equating these expressions we get <m>2n_1+1 = 2n_2+1</m>.
              Subtract one from each side of the equation to get <m>2n_1 = 2n_2</m>.
              Divide each side of the equation by two to get <m>n_1 = n_2</m>.
              Therefore, the equation <m>2x+1=a</m> has at most one integer solution.
              <m>\Box</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Edit the proof from <xref ref="part_unique_indirect_2xplus1is7"/> to prove that the equation <m>3x-4=b</m> has at most one integer solution.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
    <p>
      Recall that the one-to-one property was the uniqueness part of the definition of pairing <xref ref="defn_pairing"/>.
      Thus, we can <xref ref="pff_unique_indirect">use</xref>
      to prove that a function is one-to-one.
      Recall from <xref ref="defn_onetoone"></xref> that a function
      <m>f: X \to Y</m> is <term>one-to-one</term>
      if for each element <m>y</m> of <m>Y</m>,
      there is at most one element <m>x \in X</m> such that <m>f(x) =y</m>.
      Using the indirect approach from <xref ref="pff_unique_indirect"></xref>,
      we can prove that a function is one-to-one by showing if <m>f(x_1) = y</m> and
      <m>f(x_2)=y</m>, then <m>x_1=x_2</m>.
      There is no reason to mention <m>y</m>.
      We can prove that a function is one-to-one by showing if
      <m>f(x_1) = f(x_2)</m>, then <m>x_1=x_2</m>.
      We can restate the definition of one-to-one using this observation.
    </p>
    <remark xml:id="rem_alt_defn_onetoone">
      <title>Alternative definition of one-to-one</title>
      <p>
        Let <m>f: X \to Y</m> be a function.
        Then <m>f</m> is one-to-one exactly when it satisfies the following condition.
        For all elements <m>x_1</m> and <m>x_2</m> in <m>X</m>,
        if <m>f(x_1) = f(x_2)</m>, then <m>x_1 = x_2</m>.
      </p>
    </remark>
    <example xml:id="exam_prove_onetoone">
      <title>Prove function is one-to-one</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove that the function <m>f: \mathbb{Z} \to \mathbb{Z}</m> defined by <m>f(n) = 2n+1</m> is one-to-one,
          <xref ref="rem_alt_defn_onetoone">using</xref>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <em>Proof.</em> Let <m>n_1</m> and <m>n_2</m> be integers.
          Assume <m>f(n_1) = f(n_2)</m>.
          By the definition of <m>f</m>,
          it follows that <m>2n_1+1=2n_2+1</m>.
          Subtract one from each side of the equation to get
          <me>
            2n_1 = 2n_2
          </me>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Divide each side of the equation by two to get
          <me>
            n_1 = n_2
          </me>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Therefore, the function <m>f: \mathbb{Z} \to \mathbb{Z}</m> defined by <m>f(n) = 2n+1</m> is one-to-one.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <p>
      We can combine proof formats for existence and uniqueness to prove that there exists a unique value of <m>n</m> such that <m>P(n)</m>.
      We begin with a quick notation.
    </p>
    <remark xml:id="rem_notation_unique">
      <title>Notation for uniqueness</title>
      <p>
        There exists a unique value of <m>n</m> such that <m>P(n)</m> is denoted <m>\exists ! n ~ P(n)</m>.
      </p>
    </remark>
    <p>
      To prove that <m>\exists ! n ~ P(n)</m> we need to prove two things <mdash/> first,
      that there is at least one <m>n</m> with <m>P(n)</m> and second,
      that there is at most one <m>n</m> with <m>P(n)</m>.
      The first proves existence,
      which we can do <xref ref="pff_exists">using</xref>.
      The second proves uniqueness,
      which we can do directly <xref ref="pff_unique_direct">using</xref>.
    </p>
    <proof>
      <p>
        Prove: <m>\exists ! n ~ P(n)</m>
      </p>
      <p>
        Proof: First, consider <m>n=</m>
        (example).
      </p>
      <p>
        (Explain why <m>P(n)</m>.)
      </p>
      <p>
        Therefore, <m>P(n)</m> is true for some
        (describe type of object),
        namely <m>n=</m>
        (example).
      </p>
      <p>
        Next, assume <m>P(n)</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        (Explain why <m>n=</m> example.)
      </p>
      <p>
        Thus, if <m>P(n)</m>, then <m>n=</m> example.
      </p>
      <p>
        Therefore <m>n=</m> example is the unique
        (describe type of object)
        such that <m>P(n)</m>, namely <m>n=</m> example.
      </p>
    </proof>
    <p>
      Let's look at an example.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_exist_unique">
      <title>Proof that there exists a unique</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove that there exists a unique graph with three vertices and three edges.
        </p>
        <p>
          <em>Proof.</em> First, consider the cycle <m>C_3</m>.
          Note that <m>C_3</m> has three vertices and three edges.
        </p>
        <p>
          Next, let <m>G</m> be a graph with three vertices and three edges.
          Say the vertices are <m>u</m>, <m>v</m>, and <m>w</m>.
          There are only three possible edges between these vertices:
          <m>uv</m>, <m>uw</m>, and <m>vw</m>.
          Since <m>G</m> has three edges,
          it must have exactly those edges.
          Thus <m>G = C_3</m>.
          Therefore, there is at most one graph with three vertices and three edges,
          namely <m>C_3</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Exercises</title>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_permutations">for</xref> \subperms</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_perm_rho">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Consider the permutation with 2-line notation
            <me>
              \rho = \displaystyle \left ( \begin{array}{ccc ccc} 1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp  4 \amp  5 \amp  6 \\ 3 \amp  4 \amp  1 \amp  6 \amp  5 \amp  2 \end{array}  \right )
            </me>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  List <m>\rho(1), \rho(2), \rho(3), \rho(4), \rho(5), \rho(6)</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Draw the dot diagram for <m>\rho</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_perm_compose_dg">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Calculate the composite <m>\delta \circ \gamma</m> where
            <me>
              \delta = \left ( \begin{array}{ccc} 1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \\ 1 \amp  3 \amp  2 \end{array}  \right ) \text{ and }  \gamma= \left ( \begin{array}{ccc} 1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \\ 3 \amp  1 \amp  2 \end{array}  \right )
            </me>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  First calculate the composite by evaluating <m>\delta \circ \gamma(1)</m>,
                  <m>\delta \circ \gamma(2)</m>,
                  and <m>\delta \circ \gamma(3)</m>.
                  Write your answer in 2-line notation.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Confirm your answer using the unlabeled dot diagrams.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_perms_compose">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use dot diagrams to compose the permutations written in 2-line notation.
            Report your answer in 2-line notation.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\displaystyle \left ( \begin{array}{ccc c} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 2 \amp 4 \amp 3 \end{array} \right ) \circ \displaystyle \left ( \begin{array}{ccc c} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 3 \amp 2 \amp 4 \end{array} \right )</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\displaystyle \left ( \begin{array}{ccc c} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \\ 3 \amp 4 \amp 1 \amp 2 \end{array} \right ) \circ \displaystyle \left ( \begin{array}{ccc c} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \\ 2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \amp 1 \end{array} \right )</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\displaystyle \left ( \begin{array}{ccc c} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \\ 2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \amp 1 \end{array} \right ) \circ \displaystyle \left ( \begin{array}{ccc c} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \\ 4 \amp 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \end{array} \right )</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\displaystyle \left ( \begin{array}{ccc c} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \\ 4 \amp 2 \amp 1 \amp 3 \end{array} \right ) \circ \displaystyle \left ( \begin{array}{ccc c} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \\1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \end{array} \right )</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_iterate_rho">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use dot diagrams to calculate <m>\rho^2</m> and <m>\rho^3</m> when
            <me>
              \displaystyle \rho = \left ( \begin{array}{ccc ccc} 1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp  4 \amp  5 \amp  6 \\ 3 \amp  4 \amp  1 \amp  6 \amp  5 \amp  2 \end{array}  \right )
            </me>.
            Write the answers in 2-line notation.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_iterations_perms">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find an example of a nonidentity permutation on
            <m>\{1,2,3,4,5\}</m> that satisfies the stated condition,
            where <m>i</m> is the identity permutation on <m>\{1,2,3,4,5\}</m>.
            State your answer in 2-line notation.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\alpha^2=i</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\beta^3 = i</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\gamma^4=i</m> but <m>\gamma^2 \neq i</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\delta^5 =i</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_permutations">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What a permutation is?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to draw the standard and unlabeled dot diagram for a permutation?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to write permutation in 2-line notation?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to compose permutations using their dot diagram?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Which permutation is applied first in <m>\sigma \circ \tau</m>?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What the notation <m>\sigma^k</m> means?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_transpositions">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A <term>transposition</term> is a permutation that only switches two elements.
            For example <m>\delta = \left ( \begin{array}{ccc} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\ 1 \amp 3 \amp 2 \end{array} \right )</m> is a transposition on <m>\{1,2,3\}</m>.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Find the two other transpositions on <m>\{1,2,3\}</m>.
                  Write your answers in 2-line notation and draw their dot diagrams.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Draw the dot diagrams for each the transpositions on <m>\{1,2,3,4\}</m>..
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How can you tell from the dot diagram if a permutation is a transposition?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How many transpositions on <m>\{1,2,3, \ldots, n\}</m> are there?
                  Explain briefly.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_inverses">for</xref> \subinverses</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_perms_inverse">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use dot diagrams to calculate the inverse of each permutation.
            Write the answer in 2-line notation.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\displaystyle \delta = \left ( \begin{array}{ccc} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\ 1 \amp 3 \amp 2 \end{array} \right )</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\gamma= \left ( \begin{array}{ccc} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\ 3 \amp 1 \amp 2 \end{array} \right )</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\mu= \displaystyle \left ( \begin{array}{ccc cc} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \amp 5 \\ 1 \amp 4 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 5 \end{array} \right )</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\displaystyle \rho = \left ( \begin{array}{ccc ccc} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \amp 5 \amp 6 \\ 3 \amp 4 \amp 1 \amp 6 \amp 5 \amp 2 \end{array} \right )</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_compose_fns_at3">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Consider the functions <m>p:\mathbb{N} \to \mathbb{N}</m> defined by <m>p(n) = 10^n</m> and
            <m>q:\mathbb{N} \to \mathbb{N}</m> defined by <m>q(n) = 2n</m>.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Evaluate and simplify <m>(p \circ q)(3)</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Evaluate and simplify <m>(q \circ p)(3)</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_symmetric_group3">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Draw dot diagrams for each of the six permutations on <m>\{1,2,3\}</m>.
                  You do not need to label your dot diagrams.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  For each of those six permutations,
                  state what its inverse permutation is.
                  Hint: A permutation can be its own inverse.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_compose_bs_functions">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Consider the functions <m>\fn{trim}: \mathbb{B}^* \to \mathbb{B}</m> defined by
            <m>\fn{trim}(b) =</m> the bit sting <m>b</m> without its last bit and
            <m>\fn{append}:\mathbb{B} \to \mathbb{B}^*</m> defined by <m>\fn{append}(b)=b\bs{1}</m>,
            literally the bit string <m>b</m> with a <c>1</c> added to the right.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Calculate <m>(\fn{append} \circ \fn{trim})(\bs{1010})</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  When is <m>(\fn{append} \circ \fn{trim})(b)=b</m>?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Calculate <m>(\fn{trim} \circ \fn{append})(\bs{1010})</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  When is <m>(\fn{trim} \circ \fn{append})(b)=b</m>?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_inverse_piecewise">
        <title>\exerU inverse of piecewise function</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Consider the function <m>f: \mathbb{N} \to \mathbb{N}</m> defined by
            <me>
              f(n) =\left\{ \begin{array}{cl} n+1 \amp  \text{ if }  n \text{ is even }  \\ n-1 \amp  \text{ if }  n \text{ is odd } \end{array}  \right
            </me>.
            The dot diagram for <m>f</m> is shown in <xref ref="fig_nonid_pair_naturals"></xref>.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Calculate <m>f^2(3)</m> and <m>f^2(6)</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  It turns out that <m>f</m> is a bijection.
                  What is its inverse function?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_iterates_linear">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The function <m>g: \mathbb{R} \to \mathbb{R}</m> is defined by <m>g(x) = ax</m>,
                  where <m>a</m> is a nonzero constant.
                  Calculate <m>g^2(x)</m>, <m>g^3(x)</m>,
                  and <m>g^4(x)</m> and make a conjecture about <m>g^k(x)</m> in general.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The function <m>f: \mathbb{Z} \to \mathbb{Z}</m> is defined by
                  <m>f(n) = n + c</m> where <m>c</m> is constant.
                  Calculate and simplify <m>f^2(n)</m>,
                  <m>f^3(n)</m>, and <m>f^4(n)</m>.
                  Make a conjecture about <m>f^k(n)</m> in general.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_inverses">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  When a function is invertible?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What <m>f^{-1}(5)</m> equals if <m>f(2)=5</m> for an invertible function <m>f</m>?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to find the inverse of a permutation?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to compose functions?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What the notation <m>f^k</m> means?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Why <m>f^{-1} \circ f</m> is the identity function for any invertible function <m>f</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_inverses_of_finite_order_fns">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose <m>f:X \to X</m> is a bijection and, as usual,
            write <m>i:X \to X</m> for the identity function on <m>X</m>.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  If <m>f^2=i</m>, what does that tell you about <m>f^{-1}</m>?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  If <m>f^3=i</m>, what does that tell you about <m>f^{-1}</m>?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_pff_unique">for</xref> \subpffunique</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_direct_unique">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Give a direct proof <xref ref="pff_unique_direct"/> that the equation <m>2x+3=a</m> has at most one integer solution.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_proof_onetoone">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Prove that the function <m>f: \mathbb{Z} \to \mathbb{Z}</m> defined by <m>f(n) = n+ 3</m> is one-to-one,
            <xref ref="rem_alt_defn_onetoone">using</xref>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_prove_uniq_soln">
        <statement>
          <p>
            {Understand} Prove there exists a unique rational solution to the equation
            <m>2x + a = 2b</m> for any integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>.
            Hint: <xref ref="pff_exists_unique">Use</xref>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_pff_unique">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How we prove there is at most one of something (uniqueness)?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to prove that a function is one-to-one?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to prove there exists a unique object?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_div_alg_prove_uniqueness">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            In this exercise,
            we prove the uniqueness of the remainder in the Division Algorithm <xref ref="thm_div_alg"/>.
            To start the proof, we assume that
            <m>a = nq_1+r_1</m> and <m>a = nq_2 + r_2</m> for some integers
            <m>a,n,q_1,r_1,q_2,r_2</m> with <m>n \ne4q 0</m>,
            <m>0 \le r_1 \lt n</m>, and <m>0 \le r_2\lt n</m>.
            It is not a loss of generality to assume <m>r_1 \ge r_2</m>.
            <ol>
              <li xml:id="part_pf_div_alg_uniq_1">
                <p>
                  Set the two expressions for <m>a</m> equal to each other and solve to prove that <m>n \div (r_1-r_2)</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li xml:id="part_pf_div_alg_uniq_2">
                <p>
                  Explain why <m>0 \le r_1-r_2 \lt n</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How can parts <xref ref="part_pf_div_alg_uniq_1"/> and <xref ref="part_pf_div_alg_uniq_2"/> both be true?
                  What does your conclusion tell you about <m>r_1</m> and <m>r_2</m>?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Select Answers and Hints</title>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_perm_rho"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: The list begins 3, 4, 1, <ellipsis/>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: The dot diagram should have an arrow from 1 to 3 and an arrow from 3 to 1.
            There is also an arrow straight across from 5 to 5.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_perm_compose_dg"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: Make sure to follow the instructions in each part.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_perms_compose"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\displaystyle \left ( \begin{array}{ccc c} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 4 \amp 2 \amp 3 \end{array} \right )</m> Hint: If you got <m>\displaystyle \left ( \begin{array}{ccc c} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 3 \amp 4 \amp 2 \end{array} \right )</m> that is not correct.
            You composed the permutations in the opposite order.
            Remember, the one on the right goes first.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: The second line of the answer begins with 4.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: The answer is the identity permutation.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: The second line of the answer begins with 4.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_iterate_rho"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: <m>\displaystyle \rho^2 = \left ( \begin{array}{ccc ccc} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \amp 5 \amp 6 \\ 1 \amp 6 \amp . \amp . \amp . \amp . \end{array} \right )</m> and <m>\displaystyle \rho^3 = \left ( \begin{array}{ccc ccc} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \amp 5 \amp 6 \\ 3 \amp 2 \amp . \amp . \amp . \amp . \end{array} \right )</m>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_iterations_perms"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: <m>\alpha</m> should swap two numbers,
            such as <m>1 \to 2</m> and <m>2 \to 1</m>.
            Send the other numbers to themselves.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: <m>\beta</m> should rotate three numbers cyclically,
            such as <m>1 \to 2</m>, <m>2 \to 3</m>, and <m>3 \to 4</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: <m>\gamma</m> should rotate four numbers cyclically
            (and not just be swaps).
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: <m>\delta</m> should rotate all five numbers cyclically.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_transpositions"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Another is <m>\left ( \begin{array}{ccc} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 3 \end{array} \right )</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: There are six of them.
            Think about which pair of numbers is switched.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Most of the lines are horizontal.
            What else do you see in the dot diagram?
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: How many ways are there to choose the two numbers out of <m>n</m> to swap?
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_perms_inverse"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: <m>\delta</m> is its own inverse.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\displaystyle \gamma^{-1} = \left ( \begin{array}{ccc} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\ 2 \amp 3 \amp 1 \end{array} \right )</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Check your answer by composing <m>\mu^{-1} \circ \mu</m>.
            You should get the identity.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Check your answer by composing <m>\rho^{-1} \circ \rho</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_compose_fns_at3"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            1,000,000
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: The answer is much smaller than the answer as (a).
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_symmetric_group3"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: There are two that send <m>1 \to 1</m>,
            two that send <m>1 \to 2</m>,
            and two that send <m>1 \to 3</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Four of them are their own inverses.
            The remaining two are inverses of each other.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_compose_bs_functions"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: You should not get <c>1010</c>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: It depends on the last bit of <m>b</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: You should get <c>1010</c>.
            Make sure you show work.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Figure out what <m>\fn{append}(b)</m> is first.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_inverse_piecewise"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: <m>f^2(3) = f(f(3))=f(2)=</m>?
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: What is <m>f^2</m>?
            That tells you what <m>f \circ f</m> equals.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_iterates_linear"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: <m>g^2(x) =g(g(x))=g(ax)=a(ax) =</m>?
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: <m>f^2(n)=f(f(n))=f(n+c)=(n+c)+c=</m>?
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_direct_unique"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: Copy and edit the proof from <xref ref="act_uniqueness"></xref>
        <xref ref="part_unique_direct_2xplus1is7"/>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_proof_onetoone"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: Copy and edit the proof from <xref ref="exam_prove_onetoone"></xref>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_prove_uniq_soln"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: Before writing the proof,
        solve for <m>x</m> in terms of <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>.
        The proof has two parts.
        In the first part, consider <m>x =</m>
        (the answer you found).
        Evaluate <m>2x + a</m> when <m>x=</m> your answer and simplify to get <m>2b</m>.
        In the second part, show how you solved the equation.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>
</section>